3.

For the regression I was looking for one observation per year (e.g., 2001). Your data has one observation per Sex, State, and Year (e.g., F, Colorado, 2001).

Originally, I thought it would be simpler to filter by name, rather than filtering by count and sex because there are no male Allisons. However, explicitly filtering by sex is clearer for the reader and is more thorough!

names_year <- names_A |>
  group_by(Year) |>
  summarise(Count = sum(Count), .groups = "keep")

6.

In my first attempt, I included epsilon because I have been so used to adding it when representing the results of a linear regression. However, because we are estimating the mean, the error is already accounted for and is, thus, not needed.

\(\widehat{Allisons} = -5359999.95 + 2799.63year\)

7.

In my first attempt, I did not make a comment on the residuals (just an oversight). I have now included my observations of the pattern of the residuals.

ggplot(data = model_1, aes(x = .resid)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(density)), bins = 30, fill = "#bf5850") +
  geom_density(color = "#f7b034", lwd = 1) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Residuals", y = "Density")

The residuals are right skewed but have a mean around 0. Because the residuals are the actual - predicted value, we would hope to see residuals centered around 0, as that would indicate the regression doesnât consistently overestimate or underestimate values. However, the underestimates seem to be larger, than the underestimates.

8.

The coefficient on year is positive, meaning that each year, the number of Allisons, or the popularity of the name âAllison,â is actually predicted to increase.

Part 5

1.

Your geom_bar() plot is plotting one row per Name which ignores the âCountâ column which contains the number of Allans with that spelling each Year. So, geom_col() is what you want, so long as you provide the height of the columns (using the Count variable)!

I, at first, used geom_col to plot the Allen/Alan/Allan observations. However, I should have summarised by data before plotting to get the correct heights from Count. After summarising, I am now able to make a simple line plot that displays this information much better than before!

names_Allen <- names |>
  filter(Sex == "M",
         Name %in% c("Allen", "Allan", "Alan"))
  
names_Allen_count <- names_Allen |>
  group_by(Year, Name) |>
  summarise(Count = sum(Count))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
ggplot(data = names_Allen_count, aes(x = Year, y = Count)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = Name)) +
  theme_light() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired") +
  labs(y = "Count")

2.

names_Allen_sum <- names_Allen |>
  filter(Year == 2000,
         State %in% c("CA", "PA")) |>
  group_by(Name, State) |>
  summarise(Count = sum(Count)) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Name, values_from = Count)
